    "long_instructions": "## Do This:\r\n\r\n1. Run the code and observe what happens. \r\n2. Run the test to see if that gives you any insights into the bug.\r\n3. Decide which debugging strategy would be useful for this buggy program. \r\n4. Iteratively refine and test the updates you make to the code.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n**Unit Guide**\r\n\r\nDocument your experience with this debugging challenge:\r\n- What strategy did you use? \r\n- How did it help?\r\n- When might it be most useful in the future?",
    "start_sources": {
      "files": {
        "0": {
          "id": "0",
          "name": "main.py",
          "language": "py",
          "contents": "from neighborhood import Painter\n\npainter = Painter()\n\ndef turn_right():\n    painter.turn_left()\n    painter.turn_left()\n    painter.turn_left()\n\ndef paint_path():\n    painter.paint(\"rainbow\")\n    painter.move()\n    painter.turn_right  \n    painter.move()\n    painter.paint(\"rainbow\")\n\npaint_path\n",
          "folderId": "0",
          "active": false,
          "open": true,
          "type": "locked_starter"
        }
      },
      "folders": {
      },
      "openFiles": [
        "0"
      ]
    },
    "teacher_markdown": "**Error Type**: Logic Error (Incorrect function calls and missing function calls)\r\n\r\n**Expected Outcome**: The `Painter` should turn right and paint a rainbow path.\r\n\r\nDebugging Challenge\r\n\r\n- The first bug is that `turn_right` is a user-defined function, not a `Painter` method, so it shouldn't use dot notation.\r\n- The second bug is that `turn_right` is not being called because it's missing `()`.\r\n- The third bug is that `paint_path` is also not being called because it's missing `()`.\r\n- Hint for students: Functions must be called with parentheses to execute.",
    "display_name": "Debugging Challenge 3",
    "thumbnail_url": "https://images.code.org/8481f3c0ce363c232c7ba7c429e4141a-system.png",
    "bubble_choice_description": "You’ve carefully written instructions for the `Painter`, but it’s acting like it never got the memo. Some actions seem to be missing, and others aren’t happening when they should. Why won’t your `Painter` follow the plan?",
    "validation_file": {
      "id": "2",
      "name": "main_test.py",
      "language": "py",
      "contents": "import unittest\nfrom unittest_runner import ValidationProtocol\n\nclass TestDebugPaintPath(unittest.TestCase):\n    @classmethod\n    def setUpClass(cls):\n        \"\"\"\n        Retrieve the NeighborhoodLog once for all tests.\n        \"\"\"\n        cls.neighborhood_log = ValidationProtocol().get_neighborhood_log()\n        painter_logs = cls.neighborhood_log.painter_logs\n        # Expect exactly ONE painter\n        cls.painter_log = painter_logs[0] if painter_logs else None\n\n    def test_step1_single_painter(self):\n        \"\"\"\n        A Painter object is created.\n        \"\"\"\n        self.assertIsNotNone(\n            self.painter_log,\n            \"No Painter object found. Did you create one?\"\n        )\n        self.assertEqual(\n            len(self.neighborhood_log.painter_logs),\n            1,\n            \"Found zero or more than one Painter. Please ensure exactly one Painter.\"\n        )\n\n    def test_step2_paint_count(self):\n        \"\"\"\n        Paint two times.\n        \"\"\"\n        if self.painter_log is None:\n            self.skipTest(\"No Painter found.\")\n\n        # We expect paint_path() to call painter.paint() twice, so total 2 paints.\n        self.assertTrue(\n            self.painter_log.did_action_exactly(\"PAINT\", 2),\n            \"We expected exactly 2 paint actions.\"\n        )\n\n    def test_step3_turn_right_called(self):\n        \"\"\"\n        The Painter turns right.\n        \"\"\"\n        if self.painter_log is None:\n            self.skipTest(\"No Painter found.\")\n\n        # turn_right() => 3 consecutive TURN_LEFT actions\n        self.assertTrue(\n            self.painter_log.did_action_at_least(\"TURN_LEFT\", 3),\n            \"It doesn't look like turn_right() was actually called.\"\n        )\n\n    def test_step4_two_squares_painted(self):\n        \"\"\"\n        Paint two spaces.\n        \"\"\"\n        if self.painter_log is None:\n            self.skipTest(\"No Painter found.\")\n\n        final_output = self.neighborhood_log.final_output\n        grid_size = len(final_output)\n\n        # Count how many squares have non-None paint\n        painted_cells = 0\n        for y in range(grid_size):\n            for x in range(grid_size):\n                if final_output[y][x] is not None:\n                    painted_cells += 1\n\n        self.assertEqual(\n            painted_cells,\n            2,\n            f\"We found {painted_cells} squares painted, but expected exactly 2.\"\n        )\n",
      "folderId": "0",
      "active": false,
      "open": false,
      "type": "validation"
    }
